< review>
My AC kept turning off after few minutes after a house exterior paint job that included a pressure wash. Oscar diagnosed it as a possible fan issue. I was quoted 800$ for replacing the fan. I asked him if we can rule out the circuit breaker as that could be a potential issue but he will not look at that angle as he said that won‚Äôt be an issue and he said it must be a short in the system. Well it turns out I saved a bunch of money as it turned out to be the circuit breaker which costs just 11$ at Home Depot. Beware of being overcharged and misdiagnosed. What is more he also wanted 250$ to replace a capacitor which takes a total of 5 min to replace and 20$ for the part itself.

Edit: responding to the technician Oscar. I am telling the truth. Before posting this review, I had called his office to discuss and they never called back. Later I even offered to talk to him after he was upset I left the review but he won‚Äôt talk to me. Also some 5* reviews here are from friends and family< /review>

< text>
My freezer stopped freezing and I made the mistake of picking First Appliance Repair based on Google reviews.  I asked them up front for an idea of how much the repair might cost and they said around $220 for labor plus parts.  The guy came out and diagnosed the issue as a blockage in the freon system.  He said the repair would cost $400.  The cost sounded high but he made it sound like it was a very labor intensive repair and I needed it fixed so I said ok.  45 minutes later he was done.  I asked him why it was so expensive since it was less than an hour of labor and no parts.  He held up a can of something called Acid Scavenger and said, "This stuff costs $180!"  I went ahead and paid the bill only to find out later that Acid Scavenger costs like $20.

I called the company the next day to try to get a better understanding of what exactly they charged me for.  I asked for a manager and the first person I got said she would look into it, then never called back.  I called about five hours later and talked to another "manager" who proceeded to give me three different explanations for the cost of the repair.  They sent me an invoice that listed several other items including a piercing valve which costs like $5 plus other "parts" they supposedly used.  As far as I can tell, they charged me $180 for like $25 worth of parts.  The manager was totally unapologetic at one point saying, "Well, we fixed it for you, would you have done it yourself?"  I found everyone I dealt with to be incredibly condescending.  I suggest staying away from these guys.</text>

< text>
We love this place!  Always going back for the KFC (Korean Fried Chicken).... Went in today and saw this Ginger Soy Chicken on the menu, another favorite for My Wife & Myself.  What‚Äôs even better is, there‚Äôs many options to choose from that we haven‚Äôt even tried yet.  Thanks for the delicious Korean food Seoul Sausage!<//text>
<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOz50mxqpgXqNji6thDiQZw_3JP9epswqBB9_tg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>< GmapID>
0x80e84cf8f5e578e7:0x54c0b00eeada1d3f< /GmapID>
<date>1560134126128</date><Resp>None<//Resp>< rating>
5<//rating>
<UserId.>110512150408845886535< /UserId.></record></dataset><record>
< Review>
Middling food, high price, poor experience.

Seoul Sausage is a Korean + Sausage fusion restaurant. Dishes include Kalbi sausage with kimchi relish, chicken sausage, Korean fried chicken, and others (the menu was not fully built out yet. Combos include a can of soda and tater tots for $3 extra. You order using a tablet.

First, the food. My group tried everything that was available on the menu (the restaurant was not fully stocked since it literally JUST opened): Kalbi sausage with kimchi relish, chicken sausage, Korean fried chicken, and the tater tots. These were all... fine. Nothing really to write home about. The Kalbi sausage with Kimchi relish should have been a wow, but it could have just as easily been a bratwurst. The chicken sausage was a sweeter version of andoiulle sausage. I was unimpressed. The fried chicken was better, but needed something to go with it to balance the dish. And the tater tots were, well, tater tots. For the price ($8 for 1 small sausage on a bun) we expected to get something substantial or something that really WOWed us.

The experience. I couldn't stand the experience. Cold, detached, and not friendly. The user orders for themselves using a small terminal, but nobody saw that you had to do this. The terminals just looked like point of sale terminals, not self service kiosks. I didn't see any signage for it, either. The kitchen is open, and the chefs are right there to look at you, but they didn't help either. The presentation was a little weak - the food came in simple paper cartons and drinks are just cans of soda.

To sum up, Seoul Sausage has many of the trappings of a food truck - fusion fare, loud noise, sort of rude staff, cans of coke, high prices - but none of the charm or exceptional food.<//Review>

< text>
I am livid about my visit this evening to your restaurant in Oxnard.  I was excited to pick up dinner after a long mountain bike ride and take it home to Ojai. I have enjoyed food in the Los Angeles location and was so happy to find it in Oxnard.

First, I was told by the nice man behind the counter that he was out of cole slaw.  It was shortly after 9pm and online the hours were until 11pm but he said they changed them to 10, and they actually have "last call" at 9:30?? Honestly, I was pretty upset as that is the only reason I fell in love with the sweet/spicy sausage sandwich (the coleslaw being the sweet). I finally relented to taking it without, against my better judgement.   For some reason, it took OVER 15 minutes to prepare my food even though I was the only customer.  Weird.

I finally get home with my food and find I have only TWO of the THREE sausages that I paid for.  No coleslaw and gypped out of a dog. I will NEVER return.< /text>

< userid>
102331271894498940589< /userid>
< name>
DadMan Network</name>
<Date>1522106331496</Date>< Rating>
4</Rating>
< Text>
A bed in breakfast feel with speed of McDonald's. The coffee is drinkable black however they do have flavored creamers upon request. The food has an expected level of grease covering which the flavor reflects. The waffles are soft and spongy with a promanent vanilla flavor. The syrup being served warm is a nice touch. The eggs were fluffy and as is expected for a hometown restaurant. The bacon was thin and crisp, sausages were satisfactory if not a little bland, and the country potatoes were a little bland and needed more cooking in my opinion. Service too is fast and has a get and go feel to it as service is often gone before you finish your request. Speaking as fast as they do may correct this. The atmosphere is quaint and has a small town feel. The decor is charming and worth a visit if you enjoy a small town restaurant. Expect to spend 10-12 dollars a plate.<//Text>

<date>1495820898726< /date><Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
I've lived at eaves for the past two years and have enjoyed my time in the complex overall. Everything is very well-maintained and clean. Maintenance and office staff are always super friendly and responsive. We've had issues with various loud neighbors/pets over the multiple tenants that have lived around us, but that's to be expected with apartment living. The apartments are pretty standard, with a good amount of space (we live in a 2-bedroom unit with two people and a dog). If we do decide to move out, it will be to look for a place that's more updated with a few more amenities, like in-unit laundry and remodeled kitchens. Those are the few things that are missing that would make this place better and well-worth the rent! Avalon seems like a great management company that cares about its tenants and we would hope to find the same treatment at their other complexes!</text>

This place is awesome. The best breakfast I've had in a long time. Like since before Chuck's moves kinda good.

Price is very reasonable. 2 very large OJs, coffee, Chicken Fried Steak w/hashbrowns, and a all meat 3egg omelet w/hashbrowns came to just over $20. Portions filled the plate full. And we got over food in less than 10min!

<username>Mark Guevorkian< /username><time>1612042530066< /time>< Rating>

< review>
Based on previous reviews I was pretty excited to check out this place and hopefully find some boots for my skiis I just bought. Even as I was about to ask I asked the couple guys shoveling snow from the sidewalk in front if I could park there. First guy was like, yea ok, but the other guy just gave me this look and started shaking his head. So I nicely asked if they preferred me parking elsewhere and they pointed me across the street, fine no biggie. Next, I walk in and there are 4 guys at the checkout and I ask if they have used ski boots as I‚Äôm just getting into skiing and don‚Äôt want to spend a fortune on something yet. They point me upstairs, I ask if any of the 4 guys could help me out, and they say ‚Äúwe only help with new purchases.‚Äù Then one of the guys helps me at least size my foot, but no one came in the 40 min I was looking for an appropriate boot to help. I never found anything in my size under $400 used, so I decided I‚Äôd at least rent for the day. Guy was helpful in setting up the rental, but when I went to check out, the guy at the counter said it was $35 for the rental and $10 for the helmet. Literally 30 seconds ago the guy setting up the rental had said the helmet was $5 and earlier someone in the store said a basic rental was $30 for everything. More so I checked online before I even came To the shop because I knew there was a possibility that I may have to rent. Online it said it was $30 as well. The guy at the register said, "It's always been $35 and 10" then said he'd make an exception this one time. Their website still has it at $30 at the time of this post. He made it seem like I was being cheap and unreasonable to ask for the price that I was told and posted. It might sound like I'm cheap, but I don't think anything I asked for was unreasonable from a shop wanting someone's business. I saw a few customers in there later when I was returning and they seemed to be very nice to them since they were buying $1000s of dollars worth of gear. So if you're looking for good customer service only go here if money is not an issue for you, unfortunately that's not the case for me. Finally, maybe my fault, but I skiied on a powdery day, but the bindings were adjusted way too loose so my skiis detached every time they had any powder over them and I could barely ski. Probably mostly my fault but I think they could have set them up a little better. Aside from one guy who helped set up the rental and one guy who was kinda sorta helpful with boot fitting, this whole place had the attitude that they were too cool to help me. Will not recommend to friends or ever return. Also I try to support local shops but not when they have this attitute. Will get what I need from REI this time.<//review>

< userid>
117615166899149792473< /userid>
< name>
David Chu< /name>
<time>1519680525963<//time><rate>5</rate><Text>For my money, one of the best snowboard shops I've ever been in. And I've been in a lot. Surprisingly, not a "board shop" per se, a place that likes to get folks stoked on being outside.

Kenny is one of the good ones. Super technically informed but also able to break down ideas in a way inexperienced riders can understand. He can talk to me about sidecut and core materials, and teach me a thing or two about how to anchor my boot laces for customization of flex; but he can also walk a complete beginner through the process of deciding on a board.

I've been in a bunch and just observed them with customers, and the rest of the staff is great. Really helpful without being annoying or overbearing. Bonus, they seem to focus on staffing and supporting actual locals, not season-aire ski bums who aren't invested in the community and just looking to fund their lifestyle. I've met so many shop guys who're more interested in vibing out non-locals or maxing their commission than getting people stoked on riding, so being here is really refreshing.

They have some great boot fitters in shop. Good enough they can guarantee boot fit and will work on your boots life. Thankfully, I won't need that service on my new boots, they were able to get me pretty dialed from the outset. I have extraordinarily tough feet to fit (wide, narrow ankles, big calves), but they were able to get me set. A friend of mine wasn't able to get her boots solid after half a season, so TSH ultimately gave her a different pair. That's the kind of service that makes me pay the premium for brick-and-mortar, the the kind of service online and aggro shopkid board shops won't/can't give you.

Their demo fleet also runs super deep, and I will definitely be back later this season or next to try out a few things. They specialize in "snow surf" boards, and I reckon they have some of the best snow surfer stock in the country. High quality Japanese brands and very niche American brands, a great mix.

For my money, the best snowboard shop I've been to in either North or South Lake Tahoe, and I've been to most of them.<//Text><pictures>None</pictures>< Resp>
None</Resp>

<Rating>1</Rating><GmapID>0x80c2d14070d1b8fb:0x5416841843ccde6c<//GmapID><review>My mother passed away on 3/13/2020.  The family has 6 plots purchased many years ago. Fortunately, I found the receipt, along with a letter from Rose Hills stating that it was made and where it was stored; however, the ORIGINAL MARKER WAS LOST.  They said they would provide a new one.  Months later they installed a new marker, but it had an INCORRECT INSCRIPTION.  Months after this, I was told a correct one had been installed.  But again, another lie.  I went to visit and the incorrect marker was still there.  We couldn't have a burial or funeral for my mother, because of the pandemic, which is understandable, but 8 MONTHS LATER AND THIS IS STILL NOT RESOVED.  I ADVISE EVERYONE "DO NOT" PURCHASE ANYTHING IN ADVANCE.   Not only do I think it's unsympathetic and rude to ask grieving customers, while they are making arrangements for their loved ones, to plan their own demise, it's unwise.  Seems to be a ploy to get your money in advance knowing that the records might be lost and re-purchased unknowingly when the person actual dies.
Overall this has been a  stressful ordeal.  I CONTINUOSLY HAVE TO FOLLOW-UP.  There were also delays with the death certificates and miscommunication on other issues.   I wish our family plots were located at smaller local cemetery.  They seem to have more empathy and understanding towards the families needs. And they keep up the landscaping maintenance.  Whenever I visit, I need to have clippers and tools with me.  Also, I need to remember the flower removal day because they will throw out brand new flowers...doesn't matter if it's their birthday, etc.
I also know others who have and still are experiencing negative ordeals with Rose Hills.  I truly believe Rose Hills is more focused on financial gain then focus on the concerns of their clients!< /review><user_name>Cheri Kimi</user_name><Pics>None< /Pics>< Response>

<rating>1< /rating>< review>
Drove 3,000 miles to visit my grandfather's grave for the first time. Was met with insensitive security guards blocking the access road to the grounds due to COVID-19. And they couldn't care less about my long journey.

Since it wasn't safe for me to visit the living, I chose to go visit my ancestors and family members who had passed away with the ultimate goal of seeing my paternal grandfather's grave for the first time. He died when I was too little to know him.

Every other graveyard in the nation that I passed through had closed their offices and buildings for obvious reasons (to protect their workers) and in compliance with local ordinances. But none of them closed their grounds out of respect for those who wanted to visit the testing places of their family members. This put NO ONE at risk, and gave me NO REASON to think or suspect that rose hills would turn me away since I didn't encounter any other cemeteries that were closed.

And yet Rose Hills chose to post security guards at their access roads. Closing the GROUNDS is despicable. You cannot keep people from visiting their FAMILY members resting in a place the FAMILY paid for. Your governor's order only required that you close your buildings, not the entire property.

We can not infect the dead with COVID. The only thing putting those security officers at risk was the fact that they were posted there. This was an INSENSITIVE AND UNCALLED FOR move by the cemetery owners. It's one thing to close your gift shop and offices to protect workers but to close the grounds was a slap in the face to me after I finally had the time/opportunity to visit my grandfather's grave. I'm still in disbelief that I was turned away and that an exception was not made given how long I traveled and how many days I slept in my car to keep myself and others safe in order to get there. Disgusting.<//review>

<Text>This was written on behalf of my mother and our family.   This was our first time planning a memorial service and it was the worst experience.  The initial pick up was very respective, the 2 gentlemen that came to the house to pick up my father's body was very nice, compassionate and gentle.  The 2nd meeting was with Jenny Munoz, arrangement counselor.  She was very professional and went over the package my parents had previously paid for, but honestly, I wish she would have told us one hour is not enough, and having one hour in between services is a horrible idea.  We did not have any more communications with Rose Hills until the day of the service.  We were told to come 30 minutes prior to the service, and that was not enough time.   Our flowers were delivered but not in the chapel, to later find out all 3 arrangements were sitting in some other holding area, so thankfully they were found and delivered to the chapel in time for the service.   The family should have met with the funeral director and technology person prior to the service for the order and especially if it's done in a different language, as the musician did not understand when to play what song.   Then when an unexpected guest went up to speak for an additional 10 minutes, it threw our time line and as the last speaker of the service, I found it VERY disrespectful that your staff were already taking things down in the reception area making all sorts of loud noise. <username>Tiffany Duong</username><time>1543899536252<//time><Rating>4< /Rating>< text>
My grandparents are buried here and we come a few times a year to visit them. It's a huge memorial park with tons of graves. There's always a service or memorial going on, and while it's very sad, it's also a reminder of how we're all in this same cycle of life together.

I love the different areas and how each has a very distinct feel and theme. My grandparents are in the grass right when you enter. It's a beautiful, sunny plot with some big trees nearby. My uncle is cremated and in an urn in the Buddhist‚Äã temple area on top of the hill. Going up there, you'd forget where you are. It's almost like being in Asia. There's also a children's area, which is the saddest area to go through (for me). All the staff I've encountered here have been respectful, sensitive‚Äã, and helpful. I know they helped my family out when we were dealing with the loss of my grandparents.

They keep the grounds relatively well, for how big it is. You might have to cut away overgrowth over the tombstone you're visiting, but generally the grass is all trimmed and kept short enough.<//text>

<rate>5< /rate><review>Where do I begin? I was referred to Diane Brooks by a friend and I have to say she was truly a gift from God! Initially we were introduced to discuss the option of preplanning and like most I was hesitant and reluctant to think about or talk about death. However, I am very happy and lucky that I decided to go through with preplanning memorial services and purchasing a burial plot.

When I met Diane she took her time to answer every question that I had even the ones I may have asked several times. She was patient compassionate and truly has a great love for what she does. She throughly walked me through the process from beginning to end! Shortly after purchasing, my mother passed away and I realized how great of a decision I had made. Everything went just ask Diane said it would and she was kind enough to follow up with us through every step of the process to ensure that things went smoothly.

As uncomfortable as it may seem or sound  I recommend everyone consider preplanning. Not only does it take a load off your entire family, it will also allow you to make decisions and choose all memorial or burials options upfront. I was an emotional wreck after losing my mother and having everything already picked out before her passing allowed me to grieve her as peacefully as possible, given the circumstances, without having to make tough decision at the time of her death. Truly the best decision I could have ever made!

I am a firm believer in God and I can't thank him enough for bringing Ms. Diane into my life at such a critical time. I pray that he blesses her for being such a blessing to my entire family. Not only was she amazing, but so were each of her colleagues at Rose Hills who made an unpleasant situation such as death, as pleasant as possible with their caring and compassionate demeanor.

Thank you to everyone that I encountered at Rose Hills!

< Review>
My mother-in-law recently passed away, and my family had already made arrangements to have her cremated with another funeral home. Unfortunately the funeral home we chose did not have options for the urn for her remains, so we decided to call Rose Hills to inquire about purchasing an urn.

BIG MISTAKE.

I was very clear over the phone that I was not looking to make any arrangements; I only wanted to browse and purchase an urn. The man I spoke to was named Robert Fox, and initially he seemed very friendly and helpful and told me to come in right away and he would be able to help me out in purchasing an urn

My husband, his brother, and I went immediately and as we arrived, Robert greeted us and lead us to the showroom where the urns were on display. As soon as we entered the room, he turns to us and tells us that we might be better off purchasing an urn on Amazon or Costco because it would be cheaper. Respectfully, we explained that we had already done some browsing, but wanted to see some urns in person, and that if we saw one we liked we would purchase it, regardless of the price.

We did end up finding an urn we really liked, but wanted to look at one other place my husband had seen, and politely told Robert that we would discuss as a family and most likely return the next day to purchase. Once again, Robert suggested we look online because of the price, which we did end up doing, but we couldnt find one similar enough to the one we saw at Rose Hills.

The next day my husband, his aunt, and I returned to Rose Hills ready to purchase the urn. We asked for Robert and told him our intention. He said he would get the paperwork started and disappeared for some time. When he returned, he informed us that they were out of stock and that they would have to order it for us, and that it wouldn't be in until the following Thursday or Friday.

We were okay with this timeframe, and asked if we could pay in advance or put down a security deposit to ensure the urn would be ours. Robert said no, that we should pay when the urn arrives in stock. He took down my number and said he would call us as soon as it arrived in stock. We never received a call back, and it is already past the timeframe he gave us.

At the end of the day, it was obvious that they did not want to sell to us because we did not have my mother-in-law's services with them.

I normally wouldn't mind this, but what bothers me is that instead of telling us this was a policy, they led us on and wasted our time and energy. We are already grieving the loss of someone extremely important, and the lack of professionalism and outright deception from Rose Hills is disgusting.

I do not recommend this place in any sense of the word and would caution anyone to trust them with handling their loved ones final arrangements.</Review>
